<section id="inline_placeholderMarker">
  <title><code>placeholderMarker</code></title>
  <para>Marks up a substring inside a headword or inside a headword translation which is not part of
    the expression itself but stands for things that can take its place. An application can use the
    inline markup to format the placeholders differently from the rest of the text, to ignore the
    placeholder in full-text search, and so on. Examples: <xref linkend="ex19"/>, <xref
      linkend="ex20"/>.</para>

  <itemizedlist>
    <title>Child of</title>
    <listitem>
      <para><literal><olink targetptr="inline_headword">headword</olink></literal></para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para><literal><olink targetptr="inline_headwordTranslation">headwordTranslation</olink></literal></para>
    </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
  
  <example>
    <title>XML</title>
    <programlisting>
&lt;placeholderMarker&gt;...&lt;/placeholderMarker&gt;
    </programlisting>
  </example>
  
  <example>
    <title>JSON</title>
    <programlisting>
{
    "startIndex": ...,
    "endIndex": ...
}
    </programlisting>
  </example>
  <example>
      <title>RDF</title>
      <programlisting>
&lt;#headword&gt; dmlex:placeholderMarker [
  dmlex:startIndex 0 ;
  dmlex:endIndex 1 ] .
      </programlisting>
  </example> 
  <example>
    <title>Relational databases</title>
    <graphic fileref="modules/inline/databaseDiagrams/placeholderMarker.svg" contentwidth="16cm"/>
  </example>

</section>
